Persona Name,Role,Demographics,Pain Points,Triggers,Objections,Aspirations (Inferred),Source
George Mitchell,End User / Primary Buyer,"68 years old, retired mechanical engineer, lives in suburban Phoenix, household income $55k-$95k, bachelor's degree, has 3 children and 5 grandchildren.","Stigma of traditional hearing aids, cost of medical devices on a fixed income, generic OTC amplifiers that fail in noisy environments, social withdrawal from church/golf/restaurants, family tension over TV volume, erosion of dignity from 'pretending' to hear.","Healthcare provider recommendation from a trusted audiologist, realization of missing moments with grandchildren, frustration from spouse (Linda) over communication friction.","Technology anxiety (complexity), fear that assistive devices signal a slippery slope to loss of independence, perception of high cost as financial irresponsibility toward heirs, reluctance to look 'old' or like a 'patient'.","To maintain a sense of competent, independent manhood while staying fully engaged in family and social life without the social penalty of being perceived as disabled.","[1, 2]"
Sarah Mitchell,Caregiver / Decision Influencer,"35-55 years old, George's adult daughter, heavy online researcher.","Worry about parent's safety and social isolation, frustration watching a loved one withdraw from family events, pressure to find a solution the parent won't refuse or leave in a drawer.","Observing the parent's struggle at family dinners, fear for safety (e.g., not hearing smoke alarms), researching solutions at night on mobile devices/Reddit/AARP.","Skepticism about whether the parent will actually wear the device, concern about 'throwing away' more money on unused technology.","Peace of mind and relief from the emotional burden of caregiving, seeing her father return to his former vibrant and social self.","[2, 3]"
Dr. Priya Sharma,Audiologist / B2B Primary Buyer,"35-55 years old, owner or manager of a private audiology practice.","Losing 40-60% of patients who decline traditional hearing aids (stigma/cost), margin pressure from Costco/Amazon/OTC devices, need for competitive differentiation.","Patients walking out saying 'I'll think about it,' need for new revenue lines to offset market squeeze.","Skepticism of non-traditional brands, lack of clinical speech-in-noise data (initially), concern over battery life specs compared to medical-grade aids.","To provide universal care to all patients regardless of their budget or vanity, while growing a modern, defensible, and profitable practice.","[2, 4]"
